# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eu
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eu/ac] The **.ac** top-level domain is the Internet country code (ccTLD) for Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha, used primarily for Ascension Island (Saint Helena has its own ccTLD, .sh).
[src:eu/ac] It is administered by NIC.AC, a subsidiary of the Afilias-owned company Internet Computer Bureau.
[src:eu/ac] Registration for the domain is open to anyone.
[src:eu/ac] The registry accepts registrations of internationalised domain names.
[src:eu/ad] .ad was originally only for Andorran registrants or trademark holders and each registration had to be pre-approved.
[src:eu/ad] In 2024 the registry relaunched the TLD and revised all policies.
[src:eu/ad] Since 22 May 2024 it is a requirement to use an accredited registrar.
[src:eu/ad] Before that date, registrants could buy domains directly from the registry, which was discontinued.
[src:eu/ad] Since 22 October 2024 the registration policies were changed so that any natural or legal person worldwide can register a domain name under .ad.
[src:eu/ad] Additionally, domains are not subject to prior validation anymore and are instead processed immediately.
[src:eu/ad] Registrars outside of Andorra are also able to accredit themselves since then.
[src:eu/ad] Because .ad is an abbreviation for the word advertisement or advert, .ad has also been used in an unconventional manner as a domain hack by some advertising media.
[src:eu/ae] The internationalised country code top-level domain in the Arabic alphabet of the UAE is امارات., which is romanised as emarat.
[src:eu/ae] It is represented as `.xn--mgbaam7a8h` in Punycode.
[src:eu/ae] The domain `ae` is administered by the Telecommunications and Digital Government Regulatory Authority (TDRA) of the UAE.
[src:eu/ae] Registrations are permitted directly at the second level (unrestricted zone) or at the third level (restricted zone) beneath several category labels.
[src:eu/ae] During 2008 when ae was re-delegated to the TRA, the .aeDA published new policies in which co.ae was introduced only for local commercial companies provided that the name is connected to the business name.
[src:eu/ae] The .AE domain was originally delegated to UUNET.
[src:eu/ae] Recognising the domain should be administered in the country, the domain was transferred in 1995 to Etisalat, following a brief period of administration by the United Arab Emirates University.
[src:eu/ae] Since that time, Etisalat, through its division the UAE Network Information Center (UAEnic), has been responsible for the operation of the .ae domain.
[src:eu/ae] During GITEX 2006, TDRA announced that the .ae ccTLD management and operations will be re-delegated to TDRA from Etisalat/UAEnic, the current .ae ccTLD manager.
[src:eu/ae] A new entity called .ae Domain Administration (.aeDA) has been formed to take care of management and operations of .ae based on latest DNS and Domain Registry technologies.
[src:eu/ae] During January 2008, IANA officially re-delegated the .ae Domain to the TDRA.
[src:eu/ae] On 3 August 2008, the .aeDA took over the DNS and launched their services with the new registry system which supports registry–registrar model.
[src:eu/ae] Currently the .aeDA has accredited eight registrars from different parts of the world.
[src:eu/ae] For the first time, Internet users in the UAE will be able to register and manage their domain names under .ae automatically using an online system without going through manual process which used to take up to six weeks for domain registrations.
[src:eu/ae] As per .aeDA policies, current domain holders are allowed to transfer between registrars at no cost.
[src:eu/ae] .ae was the first ccTLD in the Arab region to use the standard Registry-Registrar model.
[src:eu/ae] As well, .aeDA is the first registry in the region to use the industry-standard Extensible Provisioning Protocol to manage its domains.
[src:eu/ae] Registrants (domain name holders) can transfer their domains from one registrar to another provided that they obtain a domain name password.
[src:eu/ae] Domain name passwords can be recovered online through .aeDA's website password-recovery.aeda.net.ae.
[src:eu/ae] After obtaining this password, registrants can supply this password to the gaining registrar who will be able to transfer it directly without dealing with the losing registrar.
[src:eu/ae] Losing registrars are prohibited from charging a fee when a domain transfer occur; however gaining registrars may do so.
[src:eu/ae] .ae domain name retail prices ranges from 30 USD to 200 USD depending on the provider and the level of support and services provided with the domain name.
[src:eu/ae] The .ae registration prices have noticeably dropped since the introduction of .aeDA.
[src:eu/ae] Prior to 3 August 2008, .ae domains were offered by Etisalat for around 41 USD per year while ac.ae, org.ae, gov.ae and sch.ae were offered for around 20 USD per year.
[src:eu/ae] International providers used to charge around 100–200 USD in order to cover the administrative cost involved in the manual registration process.
[src:eu/ae] After .aeDA's go-live in August 2008, .ae registration price declined to as low as 30 USD with international registrars.
[src:eu/ae] On 16-Sep-2012 aeDA made an announcement on reaching the 100,000 registration mark in domain names.
[src:eu/ae] During Gitex2008, .aeDA domain name counter showed over 90,000 domain names currently held in the registry, making it the largest ccTLD registry in the Arab region.
[src:eu/ae] As of May 2023, there are more than 300,000+ domains in the zone.
[src:eu/ae] 35 (21–26 June 2009) in Sydney, .aeDA representatives mentioned that aeDA's EPP-based registry system is fully compatible with IDN protocols and guidelines.
[src:eu/ae] In January 2010 ICANN announced that the UAE IDN ccTLD (DNS name: xn—mgbaam7a8h, امارات) was one of the first four new IDN ccTLDs to have passed the Fast Track String Evaluation within the domain application process.
[src:eu/ae] .aeDA, the registry operator of .ae is also the official operator for UAE ENUM Space (971).
[src:eu/ae] The ENUM space was redelegated from the incumbent operator Etisalat since 16 April 2009.
[src:eu/af] The .af domain was delegated to Abdul Razeeq in 1997, a year after Taliban fighters had captured Kabul and founded the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan.
[src:eu/af] NetNames of London initially maintained the domain following an agreement with the IANA.
[src:eu/af] Razeeq later disappeared, halting some services.
[src:eu/af] The domain was reopened on 10 March 2003, as a joint program between UNDP and the Afghan Ministry of Communications.
[src:eu/af] As of 26 August 2020, .af was used by 5,960 domains.
[src:eu/af] With the fall of Kabul in 2021, the .af domain again came under the control of the Taliban.
[src:eu/af] ICANN said it "defers decision making to within the country".
[src:eu/af] Registration is made directly at the second level, or on the third level beneath various categorised subdomains at the second level.
[src:eu/af] Third-level domains have restrictions based on which second-level domain they are registered under.
[src:eu/af] Registration on the second level is unrestricted, but more expensive.
[src:eu/af] All fees are higher for international registrants.
[src:eu/af] In 2024, a number of .af domains including "broke.af" and "queer.af" went offline.
[src:eu/af] The Afghan Ministry of Communications and IT said that they were registered through Gandi, a France-based domain name registrar, and cited Gandi's failure to make payments as the reason for suspension.
[src:eu/ag] There are no restrictions on who can register.
[src:eu/ag] In addition to its original intended use as a country code, the .ag domain has been marketed for use for agriculture-related sites, and for sites referencing the atomic symbol for silver, *Ag*.
[src:eu/ag] It also has a potential use for other domain hacks for English words that end in -ag.
[src:eu/ag] The Heritage Foundation uses .ag for URL shortening (herit.ag), as well as The Association of Former Students of Texas A&M University (tx.ag).
[src:eu/ag] The term is used in Germany, Austria, and Switzerland, but not Liechtenstein or Luxembourg.
[src:eu/ag] Zivilsenat des Oberlandesgerichtes Hamburg*) ruled in July 2004 that a *.ag* domain may only be registered by an *Aktiengesellschaft*, and then only by an AG that has the same name as the domain.
[src:eu/ag] For example, a company with shareholders in Germany having the name X AG may not register as y.ag.
[src:eu/ag] The newspaper Sermitsiaq uses the TLD since its merger with the paper Atuagagdliutit/Grønlandsposten, which was marketed as AG as an abbreviation of its combined Greenlandic and Danish names, thus implying a continuation of its identity.
[src:eu/ai] It is a popular domain hack with companies and projects related to the artificial intelligence industry (AI).
[src:eu/ai] In 2021, Google Search analyst Gary Illyes announced that ".ai" had been added to Google’s list of generic country-code top-level domains, meaning that Google would no longer infer Anguilla-specific targeting from the ccTLD.
[src:eu/ai] Identity Digital began managing the domain as of January 2025.
[src:eu/ai] Registrations within **off.ai**, **com.ai**, **net.ai**, and **org.ai** are available worldwide without restriction.
[src:eu/ai] From 15 September 2009, second level registrations within **.ai** are available to everyone worldwide.
[src:eu/ai] The minimum registration term allowed for .ai domains is 2 through 10 years for registration and renewal, and a 2-year renewal for domain transfer.
[src:eu/ai] Identity Digital is the authority in charge of managing this extension.
[src:eu/ai] Registrations began on 16 February 1995.
[src:eu/ai] The limits on the number of characters used for the domain name are, at a minimum, from 1 to 3, depending on the registrar, and always at most 63 characters.
[src:eu/ai] The character set supported for .ai domain names includes A–Z, a–z, 0–9, and hyphen.
[src:eu/ai] As of November 2022, .ai domains cannot accommodate IDN characters.
[src:eu/ai] There are no requirements for registering a domain, including local and foreign residents.
[src:eu/ai] A .ai domain can be suspended or revoked, if the domain is involved in illegal activity such as violating trademarks or copyrights.
[src:eu/ai] Usage must not violate the laws of Anguilla.
[src:eu/ai] Filing a UDRP challenge requires using one of the ICANN Approved Dispute Resolution Service Providers.
[src:eu/ai] If the domain is with an ICANN accredited registrar, they should work with the arbitrator.
[src:eu/ai] Usually this means either doing nothing or transferring a domain. .ai domains are transferable to any desired registrars as the registration of domain is done maintaining EPP.
[src:eu/ai] There used to be a whois.ai-based platform of expired domains in which those could be procured and auctioned every ten days through a standard online process.
[src:eu/ai] The last auctions of such kind closed there in December 2024; the platform had been scheduled for shutdown on 30 June 2025, but remained online in the months following that date.
[src:eu/ai] Domains cost depends on the registrar, with yearly fees ranging from US$140 (the base fee, as established by Anguilla) to $200.
[src:eu/ai] As of July 2025, the highest-valued .ai domain is an undisclosed one sold on 8 November 2023, on Escrow.com, for US$1,500,000—months after an initial $300,000 sale to the same buyer.
[src:eu/ai] Among the publicly disclosed ones, the most valued, *fin.ai*, was sold for $1,000,000 in March 2025.
[src:eu/ai] On 16 December 2017, the .ai registry started supporting the Extensible Provisioning Protocol (EPP) and migrated all of its domains onto an EPP system.
[src:eu/ai] Consequently, many registrars are allowed to sell .ai domains.
[src:eu/ai] Since that date, the .ai ccTLD has also been popular with artificial intelligence companies and organisations.
[src:eu/ai] Though such trends are primarily seen among new AI based companies or startups, many established AI and Tech companies preferred not to opt for .ai domains.
[src:eu/ai] For example, DeepMind has its domain retained at .com; Meta has redirected its facebook.ai domain to ai.meta.com.
[src:eu/ai] The registration fees earned from the .ai domains go to the treasury of the Government of Anguilla.
[src:eu/ai] As per a 2018 *New York Times* report, the total revenue generated out of selling .ai domains was $2.9 million.
[src:eu/ai] In 2023, Anguilla's government made about US$32 million from fees collected for registering .ai domains; that amounted to over 10% of gross domestic product for the territory.
[src:eu/ai] "In the years before the real breakthrough of AI, revenue from .ai domains made up less than 1% of our state income, by 2025 it will be around 47%," explained Jose Vanterpool, Minister of Infrastructure and Communications (MICUHITES), in an interview with BBC.
[src:eu/ai] The high 90% renewal rate of .ai domains and the 2025 renewal wave of domains registered in 2023 are driving another surge in state revenues, according to Domaintechnik.
[src:eu/al] AKEP recommends that .al domain registrations be performed with one of the AKEP accredited registrars.
[src:eu/al] There are also international registrars that resell .al domains.
[src:eu/al] Domain names should be between 2 and 63 characters.
[src:eu/al] Although the Albanian language has a number of special characters, the registry has not enabled the use of IDN characters.
[src:eu/al] In the past, registrations were not permitted directly at the second level, but a few existing names were "grandfathered"; they were **uniti.al**, **tirana.al**, **soros.al**, **upt.al** and **inima.al**.
[src:eu/al] In 2012 registrars started to resell .al domain names widely making them popular outside Albania as domain hacks.
[src:eu/al] In November 2014 the registry released two character domain names allowing for free landrush.
[src:eu/al] Registrations used to be only beneath the second-levels, i.e., **.com.al**, **.net.al**, **.org.al**, and **.edu.al** labeled appropriately for the type of organisation, but many now exist directly below .al.
[src:eu/al] As of November 1, 2019, the Autoriteti i Komunikimeve Elektronike dhe Postare (AKEP) has mandated that all AKEP accredited registrars begin verifying and updating the WHOIS contact information for all new domain registrations and Registrant contact modifications.
[src:eu/al] As of the end of 2022 there were 27,275 registered .al-domains.
[src:eu/eu] The .eu ccTLD was approved by ICANN on 22 March 2005 and put in the Internet root zone on 2 May 2005.
[src:eu/eu] Even though the EU is not a country (it is a sui generis intergovernmental and supranational organisation), it has an exceptional reservation in ISO 3166.
[src:eu/eu] The Commission and ICANN had extended negotiations lasting more than five years to secure its acceptance.
[src:eu/eu] The sunrise period was broken into two phases.
[src:eu/eu] The first phase, which began on 7 December 2005 was to facilitate applications by registrants with prior rights based on trademarks and geographic names.
[src:eu/eu] The second phase began on 7 February 2006 and covered company, trade and personal names.
[src:eu/eu] In the case of all Sunrise applications, the application needed to be accompanied by documents proving the claim to ownership of a certain right.
[src:eu/eu] The decision was then made by PricewaterhouseCoopers Belgium, which had been chosen as the validation agent by EURid.
[src:eu/eu] On 7 February 2006, the registry was opened for company, trade and personal names.
[src:eu/eu] In the first 15 minutes, there were 27,949 total applications, and after one hour, 71,235.
[src:eu/eu] On 7 April 2006 at 11 am CET registration became possible for non-trademark holders.
[src:eu/eu] Most people requesting domains had asked their registrars to put their requested domains in a queue, ensuring the best chance to register a domain.
[src:eu/eu] This way more than 700,000 domains were registered during the first 4 hours of operation.
[src:eu/eu] Some large registrars like GoDaddy and small registrars like Dotster suffered from long queues and unresponsiveness, allowing people to 'beat the queue' by registering through a registrar that had already processed its queue.
[src:eu/eu] By August 2006, 2 Million .eu domains had been registered.
[src:eu/eu] It was then fourth-largest ccTLD in Europe, after .de, .uk and .nl, and is one of the largest internationally.
[src:eu/eu] The number of .eu domain registrations during the year after the landrush 7 April 2006 to 6 April 2007 seems to have peaked at approximately 2.6 million .eu domains.
[src:eu/eu] The market adjustment that follows a landrush in any domain name extension ensures that the number of registered domains will fall as many speculative domain registrations that failed to be resold will not be renewed.
[src:eu/eu] This is sometimes referred to as the *Junk Dump*.
[src:eu/eu] On the morning of 7 April 2007, the number of active .eu domains stood at 2,590,160 with approximately 15,000 domains having been deleted since 5 April 2007.
[src:eu/eu] Approximately 1.5 million .eu domains were up for renewal in April 2007.
[src:eu/eu] The EURid registry software is based on the DNS.be software and domains are physically renewed at the end of the month of their anniversary of registration.
[src:eu/eu] This process differs from more sophisticated registries like that of .com TLD and other ccTLDs that operate on a daily basis.
[src:eu/eu] As with any post-landrush phase, an extension shrinks as the *Junk Dump* takes effect.
[src:eu/eu] Over one year after the launch of .eu (5 July 2007), the number of .de domains registered was 11,079,557 according to the German .de registry's statistics page, while number of German owned .eu domains according to EURid's statistics page was 796,561.
[src:eu/eu] The number of .uk domains registered was 6,038,732 according to .uk registry Nominet's statistics page.
[src:eu/eu] The number of apparently UK owned .eu domains was 344,584.
[src:eu/eu] The extent of the shrinkage of .eu ccTLD is difficult to estimate because EURid does not publish detailed statistics on the number of new domains registered each day.
[src:eu/eu] Instead it provides only a single figure for the number of active domains.
[src:eu/eu] The number of new registrations are combined with numbers of domains registered.
[src:eu/eu] Approximately 250,000 .eu domains were either deleted or moved into quarantine by 30 April 2007.
[src:eu/eu] In the intervening years the renewal rate has stabilised to approximately 80%, which is above the industry average.
[src:eu/eu] As of November 2019, according to the Tranco rank, the top 100 thousand most popular domains in the world included over 200 .eu domains.
[src:eu/eu] The commission announced on 27 April 2018 that it would like to open registration to all EU and EEA citizens, including those living outside the EU.
[src:eu/eu] The Parliament, the council, and the Commission reached an agreement on this in December 2018, and the corresponding regulation passed the Parliament on 31 January 2019.
[src:eu/eu] The 317,000 British .eu domain names were subject to Brexit negotiations because the .eu domain is reserved for European Union use.
[src:eu/eu] The .eu Brexit would have occurred on 30 March 2020, in case of no deal, but had since been postponed to January 2021.
[src:eu/eu] The UK-EU free trade deal does not cover .eu domains.
[src:eu/eu] The United Kingdom Government released guidance for British citizens regarding .eu domains in October 2020, and .eu holders with a British address attached have been contacted twice by the domain registry regarding their domains – once in October 2020, once in December 2020.
[src:eu/eu] British citizens had their .eu domains suspended on 1 January 2021 for six months, and then withdrawn on 1 July 2021 after a grace period to allow EU/EEA citizens to update the registration information to show their non-UK address.
[src:eu/eu] From 1 January 2022, they were revoked and made available for registration by other entities.
[src:eu/eu] This is the first case of its kind where an institution managing an internet top-level domain has withdrawn domains *en masse* for an entire country.
[src:eu/eu] The second-level domain .europa.eu has been reserved for EU institution sites, with institutions and agencies making the switch from .eu.int to .europa.eu domains on the Europe day of 9 May 2006.
[src:eu/eu] EURid has a rule that the second-level domain name must be in the same script as the top-level domain, so Cyrillic second-level domains must go under .ею instead of .eu, and all domain names under .ею must be spelt using Cyrillic.
[src:eu/eu] Older Cyrillic domains under .eu were cloned into .ею at its launch.
[src:eu/eu] As of March 2024, there are 1,486 registered domains under .ею.
[src:eu/eu] An application for a top-level domain using Greek letters, **.ευ** was submitted in 2016.
[src:eu/eu] The application was originally turned down because it was too visually similar to .eu.
[src:eu/eu] The Greek name of the EU is Ευρωπαϊκή Ένωση (ΕΕ), but .εε would be too visually similar to .ee, the top-level domain of Estonia.
[src:eu/eu] In 2019 steps were taken towards approving .ευ as a domain.
[src:eu/eu] As of March 2024, there are 2,595 registered domains under .ευ.
[src:eu/eu] Domain name speculation, domain name warehousing and cybersquatting are always features of the launch of any new TLD; however, this was more widespread in the case of the .eu launch.
[src:eu/eu] Bob Parsons, CEO and co-founder of GoDaddy, criticized the landrush process designed by EURid.
[src:eu/eu] Particularly, he condemned the use of shell companies by some registrars.
[src:eu/eu] These "phantom" registrars effectively had hundreds of opportunities of registering a domain whereas a genuine registrar effectively only had one opportunity to register the same domain.
[src:eu/eu] Thus some registrants were crowded out of the .eu landrush process and many generic .eu domain names are now owned by the companies using these "phantom" registrars.
[src:eu/eu] Patrik Lindén, spokesman for EURid at the time, denied the allegations by Parsons, stating that "[EURid] verified that each registrar was an individual legal entity.
[src:eu/eu] Each had to sign an agreement with us, and prepay €10,000." Parsons did not dispute that each registrar was a separate legal entity, but noted that creating such entities was trivial: "Mr.
[src:eu/eu] Linden seemed proud that the EURid registry verified that each applicant was a legal entity before it was accredited.
[src:eu/eu] Take a moment and think about what that means.
[src:eu/eu] You can form a "legal entity" for $50 – an LLC – and you are good to go.
[src:eu/eu] While speculative activity occurred with the launch of other domains, it was the scale of the activity that called into question the competence of EURid in protecting the integrity of eu ccTLD.
[src:eu/eu] The EURid organisation investigated some allegations of abuse, and in July 2006 announced the suspension of over 74,000 domain names and that they were suing 400 registrars for breach of contract.
[src:eu/eu] The status of the domains was changed from *active* to *on-hold*.
[src:eu/eu] This meant that the domains could not be moved or have their ownership changed.
[src:eu/eu] The registrars also lost their access to the EURid registration database meaning that they could no longer register .eu domain names.
[src:eu/eu] The legal action relates to the practice of domain name warehousing, whereby large numbers of domain names are registered, often by registrars, with the intention of subsequently selling them on to third parties.
[src:eu/eu] EURid rules state that applications for domains can only be made after a legitimate application has been made to a registrar.
[src:eu/eu] The 74,000 applications were made in the name of only three Cyprus registered companies – Ovidio Ltd., Fausto Ltd. and Gabino Ltd.
[src:eu/eu] The affected registrars, joined in the action by the affected registrants, obtained a provisional order from the Court of First Instance in Brussels, Belgium on 27 September 2006.
[src:eu/eu] The court ordered EURid to release the blocked domain names or else pay a fine of €25,000 per hour for each affected domain name.
[src:eu/eu] EURid complied with the court order and changed the status of the domains from *on-hold* to *active* and restored EURid registration database access to the affected registrars.
